article.description: Dikembe Mutombo scored 10 of his 22 points in a 3½-minute stretch late in the fourth quarter, and the Philadelphia 76ers beat Milwaukee 92-90 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Bucks' magic number for playoffs stuck at three

images.name: Mutombo Dikembe 020409 inline
images.caption: Dikembe Mutombo put the Bucks away with 11 fourth-quarter points.

article.linkText: Free-falling Bucks tied for eighth in East
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Unlike the fast-fading Milwaukee Bucks, Dikembe Mutombo didn't have back-to-back bad games. Mutombo scored 11 of his 22 points in the fourth quarter and grabbed eight rebounds in the Philadelphia 76ers' 92-90 victory over Milwaukee on Tuesday night. It was a drastic difference from Sunday, when Mutombo was limited to 10 points and three rebounds in 31 minutes in the Sixers' 89-87 victory over the Bucks in Philadelphia. "On Sunday, my knee was not feeling well," said Mutombo, who had both knees lathered in deep-heating lotion before the game. "The time I took off from practice yesterday and this morning's shootaround helped." The Bucks, in danger of slipping right out of the playoff picture with their 13th loss in 17 games, were wishing Mutombo had taken the night off. After Mutombo made one of two free throws with 7.4 seconds left, Ray Allen found Greg Anthony alone in the left corner, but he missed a wide-open 3-pointer. Anthony Mason grabbed the rebound and kicked it out to Tim Thomas. He missed a jumper at the buzzer. "I thought Ray made a great read on the last play," Bucks coach George Karl said. "He found Greg wide open on the baseline and he just missed the shot. Timmy got a good look off the rebound and he may have rushed it a little bit." It was reminiscent of Sunday, when Allen missed a 3-pointer at the buzzer. While the Sixers, just 5-12 in Allen Iverson's absence, inched closer to securing a playoff berth, the Bucks (39-38) slipped into a tie for seventh with Toronto, two games behind Philadelphia. Sam Cassell scored 19 for the Bucks, who complained bitterly last season about not being on TV enough, yet fell to 1-10 on national television this season with another fourth-quarter meltdown. The Bucks took a 70-68 lead into the fourth quarter, then missed 10 of their first 11 shots and fell behind 91-83 with two minutes left. Mutombo scored 10 straight points for Philadelphia as the Sixers turned a 78-76 lead into 88-79 with 3:18 left. "The fourth quarter we just played great defense," Mutombo said. "We didn't give them anything. They're great perimeter shooters. If you leave them for a 3-point shot, they're going to kill you. We were able to rotate and make them make the extra pass." Allen, in his third game back after missing six to rest his chronically sore left knee, converted a three-point play with 1:47 left and hit a 3-pointer 36 seconds later to pull the Bucks to 91-89. Mason was fouled with 31 seconds left, but missed one of two free throws. Then, Mutombo was fouled by Ervin Johnson with 7.4 seconds left and made one of two foul shots. The game was tied at 49 at halftime even though the Bucks outshot the 76ers 54 percent to 42 percent from the floor and 70 percent to 54 percent from the foul line because the Sixers made six more free throws than Milwaukee. The difference was that the Bucks, who hardly go to the basket at all, were only fouled eight times in the first half to Philadelphia's 16. "We didn't turn the ball over, we had the bulk of the free throws, and I think we had a lot of second opportunities," Sixers guard Eric Snow said. "They didn't have any free throws. That's what balanced it out." Karl complained about the officiating after the Sixers got to the line 39 times to Milwaukee's 27. "The whistles we're getting are just, you know, on our homecourt the other team shoots almost 40 free throws? That's incredible," he said. "And Philly beats you up. Philly's known for its defense, fouling and old-fashioned street ball. It kind of goes with the cliche that the team that fouls the most doesn't get called for it." But Mason once again slammed his own team for its bad execution and tiresome excuses. "We're all right, don't worry, we're not that far -- that's nonsense," Mason said. "We're far from being a good team and we're not all right. Until we start sensing that and start playing like it's an emergency situation we're not going to change it."

Game notes
Philadelphia won the season series 3-1. ... Injured Bucks G Michael Redd, out since March 26 with a sprained knee, took stationary shots during the shootaround and said he hoped to return to practice Thursday. ... Bucks G Rafer Alston, suspended for one game last week for missing practice, was back in uniform. He had failed to rejoin the team in Philadelphia on Sunday as planned because of travel problems. ... Allen scored 14 points in 26 minutes.
